<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="aws-cli-setup">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>infrastructure-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Install and configure AWS CLI v2 with named profiles, credential files, and environment variables for multi-account and multi-region workflows.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>aws</tag>
      <tag>cli</tag>
      <tag>credentials</tag>
      <tag>profiles</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>aws</category>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="aws-iam-practical-patterns"/>
      <ref slug="aws-ec2-provisioning"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>AWS CLI v2 Setup and Profile Management</title>

    <summary>Install AWS CLI v2 on Linux, configure named profiles and credential files, and manage authentication via environment variables for multi-account, multi-region workflows. Profile-per-environment isolation prevents credential leaks between dev and production.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>AWS CLI v2 is the primary operational surface for every AWS infrastructure task. Proper profile separation (default, production, development) prevents accidental operations in the wrong account. Environment-variable overrides let CI/CD pipelines inject temporary credentials without touching the shared credentials file. Understanding the credential resolution order prevents hard-to-debug authentication errors.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up a new developer workstation or CI runner for AWS access.</item>
        <item>Adding a new AWS account (dev, staging, prod) to an existing workflow.</item>
        <item>Configuring assume-role profiles for cross-account access.</item>
        <item>Debugging authentication failures (wrong profile, expired tokens).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>EC2 instances and ECS tasks — use IAM instance roles/task roles; no CLI credentials file needed.</item>
        <item>Lambda functions — use execution roles; never embed credentials.</item>
        <item>Production automation — prefer IAM roles with STS AssumeRole over long-lived access keys.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="installation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Install AWS CLI v2 (not v1) on Linux by downloading the official zip from awscli.amazonaws.com and running the bundled installer. Verify with `aws --version` showing `aws-cli/2.x`.</statement>
        <rationale>AWS CLI v2 supports SSO, IMDSv2, and all current API features. v1 is no longer recommended and lacks SSO integration.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="AWS CLI v2 Linux install">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Install AWS CLI v2 (Linux)
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o "awscliv2.zip"
unzip awscliv2.zip
sudo ./aws/install

# Verify
aws --version
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="profile-management">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use named profiles (one per account/environment) rather than overwriting the default profile. Always specify --profile or set AWS_PROFILE when running commands against non-default accounts.</statement>
        <rationale>Named profiles prevent accidental operations in the wrong account. A default profile pointing to production is a common source of destructive incidents.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Configure and use named profiles">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Configure default profile
aws configure
# Input: Access Key ID, Secret Access Key, Region, Output format

# Configure named profile
aws configure --profile production

# List profiles
aws configure list-profiles

# Use specific profile
aws s3 ls --profile production
export AWS_PROFILE=production
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="environment-variables">
      <p>Environment variables take precedence over credential files. Use them in CI/CD pipelines to inject temporary STS credentials without touching the shared file.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Authentication via environment variables">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Authentication
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="your-access-key"
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="your-secret-key"
export AWS_SESSION_TOKEN="your-session-token"

# Region
export AWS_DEFAULT_REGION="us-east-1"
export AWS_REGION="us-east-1"

# Output format
export AWS_DEFAULT_OUTPUT="json"  # json | text | table | yaml
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="credentials-and-config-files">
      <p>The credentials file (~/.aws/credentials) holds access keys. The config file (~/.aws/config) holds region, output format, and role-assumption chains. For cross-account access, define a profile with role_arn and source_profile so STS AssumeRole happens transparently.</p>

      <example type="good" title="~/.aws/credentials with named profiles">
        <code lang="ini"><![CDATA[
# ~/.aws/credentials
[default]
aws_access_key_id = YOUR_ACCESS_KEY
aws_secret_access_key = YOUR_SECRET_KEY

[production]
aws_access_key_id = PROD_ACCESS_KEY
aws_secret_access_key = PROD_SECRET_KEY

[development]
role_arn = arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/DevRole
source_profile = default
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="~/.aws/config with region and role assumption">
        <code lang="ini"><![CDATA[
# ~/.aws/config
[default]
region = us-east-1
output = json

[profile production]
region = eu-west-1
output = table

[profile development]
region = us-west-2
role_arn = arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/DevRole
source_profile = default
]]></code>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Storing long-lived access keys for production in the credentials file on a developer workstation.</description>
        <reason>If the workstation is compromised, production keys are exposed. Use assume-role chains with short-lived STS tokens from a base set of dev credentials.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the default profile for both dev and production accounts.</description>
        <reason>A mistyped command with no --profile flag will execute in whichever account the default points to. Named profiles plus AWS_PROFILE in shell prompts prevent this.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>AWS CLI v2 installed and `aws --version` returns `aws-cli/2.x`.</check>
      <check>Named profile per account (default = sandbox or dev only).</check>
      <check>Production credentials use role assumption, not long-lived keys.</check>
      <check>CI/CD uses environment variables (AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, AWS_SESSION_TOKEN), not credentials file.</check>
      <check>AWS_DEFAULT_REGION set so commands don't require --region flag.</check>
    </checklist>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/"/>
      <link href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/reference/"/>
      <ref slug="aws-iam-practical-patterns"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
